{"@context":"http://www.w3.org/ns/anno.jsonld","id":"urn:uuid:demo-0001","type":"Annotation","created":"2026-03-12T10:00:00+00:00","target":{"selector":{"type":"TextQuoteSelector","exact":"every additional period of survival implies a longer remaining life expectancy","prefix":"framework, ","suffix":".\n\nThe concept"}},"body":[{"type":"TextualBody","value":"Is this actually supported empirically, or is it more of a heuristic?","creator":{"type":"Person","name":"Me"},"created":"2026-03-12T10:00:00+00:00"},{"type":"TextualBody","value":"It's a heuristic with some empirical backing. Taleb cites power-law distributions in book longevity data, and similar patterns appear in Broadway show lifespans. But it's not a universal law — it applies best to things without built-in expiration dates.","creator":{"type":"Software","name":"AI"},"created":"2026-03-12T10:01:30+00:00"},{"type":"TextualBody","value":"Good distinction. Should probably note that in the text — maybe add a caveat about the domain of applicability.","creator":{"type":"Person","name":"Me"},"created":"2026-03-12T10:03:00+00:00"}],"scholia:status":"open"}
{"@context":"http://www.w3.org/ns/anno.jsonld","id":"urn:uuid:demo-0002","type":"Annotation","created":"2026-03-12T10:05:00+00:00","target":{"selector":{"type":"TextQuoteSelector","exact":"Unix, SQL, and Lisp keep reappearing","prefix":"why ","suffix":" despite periodic"}},"body":[{"type":"TextualBody","value":"Might add C to this list — it's the canonical example.","creator":{"type":"Person","name":"Me"},"created":"2026-03-12T10:05:00+00:00"}],"scholia:status":"open"}
{"@context":"http://www.w3.org/ns/anno.jsonld","id":"urn:uuid:demo-0003","type":"Annotation","created":"2026-03-12T09:10:00+00:00","target":{"selector":{"type":"TextQuoteSelector","exact":"Exponential backoff with jitter","prefix":"defense. ","suffix":" prevents"}},"body":[{"type":"TextualBody","value":"Should specify which jitter strategy — full jitter, equal jitter, or decorrelated jitter.","creator":{"type":"Person","name":"Me"},"created":"2026-03-12T09:10:00+00:00"},{"type":"TextualBody","value":"Full jitter is almost always the right choice. I'll add a citation to the AWS architecture blog post (Brooker, 2015).","creator":{"type":"Software","name":"AI"},"created":"2026-03-12T09:11:00+00:00"},{"type":"TextualBody","value":"Done, updated the text. Resolving.","creator":{"type":"Person","name":"Me"},"created":"2026-03-12T09:15:00+00:00"}],"scholia:status":"resolved","scholia:resolvedAt":"2026-03-12T09:15:30+00:00"}
{"@context":"http://www.w3.org/ns/anno.jsonld","id":"urn:uuid:demo-0004","type":"Annotation","created":"2026-03-12T09:20:00+00:00","target":{"selector":{"type":"TextQuoteSelector","exact":"Idempotency is the foundation that makes retries safe","prefix":"\n\n","suffix":". If an"}},"body":[{"type":"TextualBody","value":"'Foundation' is too strong — you can have safe retries without idempotency if you use exactly-once delivery.","creator":{"type":"Person","name":"Me"},"created":"2026-03-12T09:20:00+00:00"},{"type":"TextualBody","value":"Exactly-once is effectively impossible in the general case (FLP impossibility, Two Generals problem). Systems that claim exactly-once typically mean effectively-once through idempotent processing.","creator":{"type":"Software","name":"AI"},"created":"2026-03-12T09:21:00+00:00"},{"type":"TextualBody","value":"Hmm, resolved.","creator":{"type":"Person","name":"Me"},"created":"2026-03-12T09:25:00+00:00"},{"type":"TextualBody","value":"Actually wait — Kafka's transactional API does provide exactly-once within a pipeline. Reopening.","creator":{"type":"Person","name":"Me"},"created":"2026-03-12T09:30:00+00:00"}],"scholia:status":"open"}
{"@context":"http://www.w3.org/ns/anno.jsonld","id":"urn:uuid:demo-0005","type":"Annotation","created":"2026-03-12T10:00:00+00:00","target":{"selector":{"type":"TextQuoteSelector","exact":"$E = mc^2$","prefix":"equivalence ","suffix":" is perhaps"}},"body":[{"type":"TextualBody","value":"Should this use \\( E = mc^2 \\) instead for Pandoc compatibility? Dollar-sign delimiters can be ambiguous with currency.","creator":{"type":"Person","name":"Me"},"created":"2026-03-12T10:00:00+00:00"},{"type":"TextualBody","value":"Pandoc handles both syntaxes with --mathjax. The dollar-sign form is more widely recognized in markdown and works correctly as long as the opening $ is not followed by a space.","creator":{"type":"Software","name":"AI"},"created":"2026-03-12T10:01:00+00:00"}],"scholia:status":"open"}
{"@context":"http://www.w3.org/ns/anno.jsonld","id":"urn:uuid:demo-0006","type":"Annotation","created":"2026-03-12T10:02:00+00:00","target":{"selector":{"type":"TextQuoteSelector","exact":"def forward_diff(f, x, h=1e-8):\n    \"\"\"Compute f'(x) using forward difference.\"\"\"\n    return (f(x + h) - f(x)) / h","prefix":"```python\n","suffix":"\n\n# Catastrophic"}},"body":[{"type":"TextualBody","value":"The default h=1e-8 is reasonable for forward difference but suboptimal. The theoretically optimal step is h ≈ sqrt(epsilon_mach) ≈ 1.5e-8, so this is close.","creator":{"type":"Person","name":"Ravi"},"created":"2026-03-12T10:02:00+00:00"},{"type":"TextualBody","value":"Good catch. For central difference the optimal is cbrt(epsilon_mach) ≈ 6e-6, which is a bigger discrepancy if someone reuses this default.","creator":{"type":"Software","name":"AI"},"created":"2026-03-12T10:03:00+00:00"},{"type":"TextualBody","value":"Right. We should probably parameterize by method rather than using a single default.","creator":{"type":"Person","name":"Ravi"},"created":"2026-03-12T10:04:00+00:00"},{"type":"TextualBody","value":"That's a clean API: `diff(f, x, method='central')` with each method choosing its own optimal h. Keeps the simple interface but avoids the trap.","creator":{"type":"Software","name":"AI"},"created":"2026-03-12T10:05:00+00:00"},{"type":"TextualBody","value":"I like that. Let's update the example to show both methods with their respective defaults.","creator":{"type":"Person","name":"Me"},"created":"2026-03-12T10:06:00+00:00"}],"scholia:status":"open"}
{"@context": "http://www.w3.org/ns/anno.jsonld", "id": "urn:uuid:demo-0001", "type": "Annotation", "created": "2026-03-12T10:00:00+00:00", "target": {"selector": {"type": "TextQuoteSelector", "exact": "se survival is evi", "prefix": "ge is inherently good, but\nbecau", "suffix": "dence of fitness. This is why Un"}}, "body": [{"type": "TextualBody", "value": "Is this actually supported empirically, or is it more of a heuristic?", "creator": {"type": "Person", "name": "Me"}, "created": "2026-03-12T10:00:00+00:00"}, {"type": "TextualBody", "value": "It's a heuristic with some empirical backing. Taleb cites power-law distributions in book longevity data, and similar patterns appear in Broadway show lifespans. But it's not a universal law \u2014 it applies best to things without built-in expiration dates.", "creator": {"type": "Software", "name": "AI"}, "created": "2026-03-12T10:01:30+00:00"}, {"type": "TextualBody", "value": "Good distinction. Should probably note that in the text \u2014 maybe add a caveat about the domain of applicability.", "creator": {"type": "Person", "name": "Me"}, "created": "2026-03-12T10:03:00+00:00"}], "scholia:status": "open", "modified": "2026-03-15T16:13:19.146315+00:00"}
